# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: michael-argyle-psychologist
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] Furnham has a broad range of research interests within the field of psychology.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] He has explored topics within applied, economic, health, occupational, social and differential psychology.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] As of 2018, he has published 92 books and over 1,200 peer-reviewed journal articles.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] Furnham is a fellow of the British Psychological Society; he was granted the British Psychological Society Award for Academic Contribution to Practice in 2011.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] Furnham was born on 3 February 1953 to British parents in Port Shepstone, in the Union of South Africa.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] His father was a newspaper printer and publisher, and his mother was a nurse.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] In 1970, at the age of sixteen, he began his university education at the University of Natal Pietermaritzburg Campus, completing a Bachelor of Arts degree in 1972 and an Honours Bachelor of Arts degree in 1973, focusing on history, psychology, and theology.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] He completed his Master of Arts in 1974, composing his thesis on cross-cultural conformity and field dependence.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] In 1975, he completed an economics master's degree at the University of London, focusing his research on verbal, vocal, and visual cues and perception.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] He later completed a Master of Science at the University of Strathclyde, where he researched sex and class factors in the perception of social episodes.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] In 1981, Furnham completed a doctorate at Oxford and later received a DSc from London in 1991 and a DLitt from Natal in 1997.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] Adrian Furnham is currently a professor of psychology at University College London.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] Before his current placement, he had previously lectured at numerous institutes, including Pembroke College, Oxford, the University of New South Wales, and the University of the West Indies.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] Furthermore, he also taught management at both the Hong Kong University Business School and Henley Management College.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] In 2009, he was appointed adjunct professor of management at the Norwegian School of Management.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] Furnham has been recognized as a Chartered Occupational Psychologist.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] In addition to his professorial roles at several universities, Furnham is an active member of many different associations.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] He is a Fellow of the British Psychological Society, and was identified as the second most productive psychologist in 1995.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] He is also currently the elected president of the International Society for the Study of Individual Differences, as well as the founder and director of Applied Behavioral Research Associates (ABRA), a psychological consultancy.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] Furnham's work was used at universities and other associations.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] He also consulted for many international companies in assisting them with top team development, creating systems for performance management, psychometric testing, and developing leadership skills.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] Following these experiences, he was elected Fellow of the Leadership Trust in 2010, Academician of the Learned Society of the Social Sciences in 2010, and received the British Psychological Society Award for Academic Contribution in 2011.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] He has written over 92 books, and many of them have been translated into different languages, including Chinese, French, German, Italian, Japanese, Korean, Polish, Russian, Portuguese, and Spanish.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] He has been a columnist in multiple management magazines such as *Mastering Management* and *Human Resources.* He is also a regular contributor to national and international radio and television channels such as BBC, CNN, and ITV.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] Furnham has documented different scales that measure the same thing and compared their validity and reliability.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] He did this through reviewing old and new personality tests.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] Some examples of his extensive reviews include Tolerance of Ambiguity (co-authored with Ribchester and Marks), Belief in a Just World, and the Protestant Work Ethic.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] Furnham has developed several tests throughout his career.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] He adapted existing ideas to create specific measures such as the *Economic Locus of Control* in 1986 and the *Organisational Attributional Style Questionnaire* in 1992.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] He co-developed the *Trait Emotional Intelligence Questionnaire*, a self-report inventory that assesses the sampling domain of trait emotional intelligence, with his PhD student Dino Petrides in 2006.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] He also developed the *High Flyer Trait Inventory* (formerly High Flying Personality Inventory), with his colleague Ian Macrae in 2014.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] The High Flyer Trait Inventory is a measure of personality traits directly related to workplace behaviours, thoughts, and perceptions of oneself and others.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] To this day, Furnham has maintained an interest in the distant relationship between the two pillars differential psychology.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] Furnham had given his opinion on this topic to the International Society for the Study of Individual differences.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] He works on this topic with the help of his PhD students.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] Beginning early on Furnham took a great interest in self-awareness and self-estimating intelligence, in which he published many studies on.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] The findings of his studies revealed that males tend to estimate their general intelligence by 5-15 IQ points higher than females, that these sex differences persist across generations, and that they are cross-culturally consistent.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] Furnham was introduced to the dark side personality by Robert Hogan.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] Dark side personalities are those that portray dysfunctional behaviours and beliefs towards others.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] For instance, Psychopaths fall under this category.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] These types of people do not consider how their actions affect their reputation, and, although this may seem like deviant behaviour, it also seems to help them climb the corporate ladder.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] Dark side personality research was based on the DSM-III.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] Using the Hogan Development Survey in various studies, Furnham was able to collect sufficient amounts of data, which later on aided in studying misbehaviour at work.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] According to the HDS, mischievous people were considered to be extraverts, disagreeable, deliberate, and stable.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] They scored high on the excitement scale and low on the consciousness scale.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/adrian-furnham] Furnham has written multiple papers as well as two books on this topic.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/alma-mater] In its earliest usage, *alma mater* was an honorific title for various mother goddesses, especially Ceres or Cybele.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/alma-mater] Later, in Catholicism, it became a title for Mary, mother of Jesus.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/alma-mater] By the early 17th century, the nursing mother became an allegory for universities.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/alma-mater] Used by many schools in Europe and North America, it has special association with the University of Bologna, whose motto *Alma Mater Studiorum* ("nurturing mother of studies") emphasizes its role in originating the modern university.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/alma-mater] Several university campuses in North America display artistic representations of *Alma Mater*, depicted as a robed woman wearing a laurel wreath crown.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/alma-mater] The earliest and of these is the bronze *Alma Mater* statue at Columbia University, designed in 1901 by Daniel Chester French.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/alma-mater] In the US the term *alma mater* is often used to describe a school song.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/alma-mater] Although *alma* (nourishing) was a common epithet for Ceres, Cybele, Venus, and other mother goddesses, it was not frequently used in conjunction with *mater* in classical Latin.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/alma-mater] After the fall of Rome, the term was used in Christian liturgy to describe Jesus' mother, Mary.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/alma-mater] "Alma Redemptoris Mater" is a well-known eleventh century antiphon devoted to Mary.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/alma-mater] The earliest documented use of the term to refer to a university is in 1600, when the University of Cambridge printer, John Legate, began using an emblem for the university press.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/alma-mater] The first-known appearance of the device is in William Perkins', *A Golden Chain*, a book first printed by Legate in 1600.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/alma-mater] On the title-page, the Latin phrase *Alma Mater Cantabrigia* ("nourishing mother Cambridge") is inscribed on a pedestal bearing a lactating woman wearing a mural crown.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/alma-mater] In reference works of English etymology, often the first university-related usage is cited as 1710, when an academic mother figure is mentioned in a remembrance of Henry More by Richard Ward.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/alma-mater] Many historic European universities have adopted *Alma Mater* as part of the Latin translation of their official name.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/alma-mater] The Latin name of the University of Bologna, *Alma Mater Studiorum* (nourishing mother of studies), refers to its status as the oldest continuously operating university in the world.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/alma-mater] At other European universities, such as the Alma Mater Lipsiensis in Leipzig, Germany, or Alma Mater Jagiellonica, Poland, the title emphasizes historic ties to a founding city or dynasty.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/alma-mater] The Alma Mater Europaea in Salzburg, Austria, an international university founded by the European Academy of Sciences and Arts in 2010, uses the term as its official name.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/alma-mater] In the United States, the College of William & Mary in Williamsburg, Virginia, has been called the "Alma Mater of the Nation" because of its ties to the founding of the country.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/alma-mater] At Queen's University in Kingston, Ontario, and the University of British Columbia in Vancouver, British Columbia, the main student government is known as the Alma Mater Society.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/alma-mater] Sculptures of *Alma Mater* are found on several North American university campuses.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/alma-mater] In 1901, to commemorate the opening of the Low Library, Columbia University commissioned Daniel Chester French to design a bronze statue for the library's steps.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/alma-mater] French chose the *Alma Mater* to allegorically embody the university without depicting its founder, King George II.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/alma-mater] A similar sculpture, cast in 1919 by Mario Korbel, sits on the main entrance steps at the University of Havana.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/alma-mater] Other tributes to *Alma Mater* include Lorado Taft's *1929 sculpture* at the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign and Cyrus Dallin's 1925 sculpture at the Mary Institute in 1925, commissioned by Washington University supporters.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/alma-mater] An altarpiece mural in Yale University's Sterling Memorial Library, painted in 1932 by Eugene Savage, depicts the *Alma Mater* as a bearer of light and truth, standing in the midst of figures representing the arts and sciences.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/benjamin-beit-hallahmi] Benjamin Beit-Hallahmi was born in 1943 in Tel Aviv, Israel.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/benjamin-beit-hallahmi] He served in the Israel Defense Forces from 1963 to 1966.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/benjamin-beit-hallahmi] He received his BA degree from the Hebrew University of Jerusalem and went on to receive his MA and PhD in clinical psychology from Michigan State University in 1968 and 1970, respectively.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/benjamin-beit-hallahmi] His work particularly focuses on psychology of religion.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/benjamin-beit-hallahmi] Beit-Hallahmi taught at, among others, Hebrew University of Jerusalem, University of Pennsylvania, and the University of Michigan.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/benjamin-beit-hallahmi] He was a psychology professor and senior lecturer at the University of Haifa from 1973 on.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/benjamin-beit-hallahmi] He has authored several books, both on new religious movements or cults, and the relationship between Judaism and Zionism.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/benjamin-beit-hallahmi] He has described himself as a progressive and a critic of Israel.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/benjamin-beit-hallahmi] He has published several books criticizing Israel.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/benjamin-beit-hallahmi] In the 1980s, he advocated the establishment of a binational state, and was a charter member of the group Council of Israel-Palestine Peace.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/benjamin-beit-hallahmi] A writer for the *Encyclopaedia Judaica* called him a "leading authority on the social psychology of religion".
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/benjamin-beit-hallahmi] A review in the *Journal of Palestine Studies* of *The Israeli Connection* was positive, saying it painted a valuable portrait of Israel's geopolitical relations, as did a review in *Archives de sciences sociales des religions*.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/benjamin-beit-hallahmi] He criticized the book as very selectively presenting facts to paint the picture Beit-Hallahmi wanted to portray; he negatively contrasted Beit-Hallahmi's work against the work of Palestinian scholar Bishara Bahbah.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/benjamin-beit-hallahmi] A review in *Africa Today* called it overstated and polemical, but said even if one agreed with him the "quality of his evidence and data would lead one to raise serious questions about his qualifications as a scholar".
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/benjamin-beit-hallahmi] In the field of new religious movement and cult studies, Beit-Hallahmi is known as very critical of new religious movements.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/benjamin-beit-hallahmi] He has written that in the 1980s a conspiracy of scholars collaborated to blacklist critics of cults.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/benjamin-beit-hallahmi] Previously, in 1987, anti-cult psychologist Margaret Singer said he was too sympathetic to cults, when he criticized the concept of brainwashing in 1987, and accused him of being part of the same conspiracy.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/benjamin-beit-hallahmi] He contributed to the 2001 book *Misunderstanding Cults: Searching for Objectivity in a Controversial Field*, which has pieces from both the "pro and anti-cult" sides, as a "cult basher".
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/benjamin-beit-hallahmi] He has criticized the Church of Scientology and said it is not a religion.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/benjamin-beit-hallahmi] Beit-Hallahmi authored a 2025 book that examines the relationship between academics in the new religious movement research network and the groups they elect to study, titled *Academic Advocacy for New Religious Movements: Of Apocalypse and Justice*.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/benjamin-beit-hallahmi] Several of Wright's publications are criticized extensively in the book.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/benjamin-beit-hallahmi] Beit-Hallahmi refers, for example, to claims Wright makes in defense of the Rajneesh movement with regards to the 1984 Rajneeshee bioterror attack and other criminal activity.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/benjamin-beit-hallahmi] Wright was very critical of the work, calling it an "unfortunate tome" and an "exercise in conspiracy theory".
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/benjamin-beit-hallahmi] He wrote that "it appears that Beit-Hallahmi has an agenda and the 'facts' are made to fit that agenda".
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/benjamin-beit-hallahmi] He also criticized the manuscript for, in his view, being full of mistakes and typographical errors.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/communication-cycle] Michael Argyle was born in Nottingham on 11 August 1925.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/communication-cycle] He was educated at Nottingham High School for Boys.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/communication-cycle] After completing with distinction a Royal Air Force science course at the University of Cambridge he trained as a navigator in Canada (1943-7).
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/communication-cycle] In June 1949 Michael married Sonia Kemp and they had four children, Miranda (1952), Nick (1954), Rosalind (1957) and Ophelia (1963).
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/communication-cycle] After the war he read part one in moral sciences at Emmanuel College, Cambridge and in 1950 graduated with first class honours in experimental psychology.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/communication-cycle] Following two years of postgraduate study in Cambridge he became the first ever lecturer in social psychology at the University of Oxford, where he worked for many years.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/communication-cycle] At the time, Oxford University was, along with the London School of Economics, one of only two universities in the United Kingdom to have a department of social psychology.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/communication-cycle] He became a fellow of the newly founded Wolfson College, Oxford in 1966 and three years later a reader.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/communication-cycle] He was one of the very early pioneers of social psychology in the UK and Europe and helped to initiate the *British Journal of Social and Clinical Psychology* as the first social psychology editor (1961-7).
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/communication-cycle] In 1968 he set up a social skills training programme at Littlemore Hospital, Oxford.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/communication-cycle] He chaired the social psychology section of the British Psychological Society twice (1964-7, 1972-4).
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/communication-cycle] Distinguished psychologists and sociologists from all over the world visited the research group he set up at Oxford.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/communication-cycle] He received honorary doctorates from the universities of Oxford (1979), Adelaide and Brussels (1982) and an honorary fellowship of the British Psychological Society (1992).
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/communication-cycle] In 1990 The International Society of the Study of Personal Relationships in 1990 gave him a distinguished career contribution award.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/communication-cycle] After his retirement, he became Professor Emeritus at Oxford Brookes University.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/communication-cycle] He regularly attended social psychology conferences.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/communication-cycle] He had a great passion for Scottish country dancing.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/communication-cycle] His wife Sonia died in 1999 and Argyle died on 6 September 2002, at the age of 77, of injuries suffered in a swimming accident.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/communication-cycle] Some of Argyle's best-known contributions were to this field.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/communication-cycle] One of his best-known books relevant to this field, The Psychology of Interpersonal Behaviour, became a best-seller.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/communication-cycle] Argyle made modifications in 1972 to the communication cycle initially developed by Charles Berner in 1965.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/communication-cycle] The communication cycle involves six steps: someone decides to communicate an idea, encodes it, and sends it; someone else receives it, decodes it and understands it.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/communication-cycle] Feedback demonstrates understanding (e.g. an action is performed or a reply message is encoded and sent).
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/communication-cycle] The model allows for the possibility of distortion at either the encoding or decoding stage.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/communication-cycle] Argyle, a committed Christian, published empirical works on the psychology of religion.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/communication-cycle] His early work in this field was summarized in his book Religious Behaviour (1958).
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/communication-cycle] He also collaborated with Benjman Beit-Hallahmi to produce a later book, "The Psychology of Religious Beliefs, Behaviour and Experience" (1997).
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/communication-cycle] Both books show Argyle's commitment to empiricism in psychology, and list results of surveys into topics such as beliefs in the afterlife or frequencies of religious experience in the general population.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/communication-cycle] One of Argyle's most notable later contributions was to the psychology of happiness.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/communication-cycle] Keen that more research should be done in this field, he published "The Psychology of Happiness" in 1987, 2nd edition 2001.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/communication-cycle] In this book he listed and discussed empirical findings on happiness, including that happiness is indeed promoted by relationships, faith, sex, eating, exercise, music, success, etc., but probably not by wealth.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/discourse-analysis] The objects of discourse analysis (discourse, writing, conversation, communicative event) are variously defined in terms of coherent sequences of sentences, propositions, speech, or turns-at-talk.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/discourse-analysis] Contrary to much of traditional linguistics, discourse analysts not only study language use 'beyond the sentence boundary' but also prefer to analyze 'naturally occurring' language use, not invented examples.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/discourse-analysis] Text linguistics is a closely related field.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/discourse-analysis] The essential difference between discourse analysis and text linguistics is that discourse analysis aims at revealing socio-psychological characteristics of a person/persons rather than text structure.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/discourse-analysis] There is ongoing discussion about whether Austria-born Leo Spitzer's *Stilstudien* (*Style Studies*) of 1928 is the earliest example of *discourse analysis* (DA).
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/discourse-analysis] Michel Foucault translated it into French.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/discourse-analysis] However, the term first came into general use following the publication of a series of papers by Zellig Harris from 1952 reporting on work from which he developed transformational grammar in the late 1930s.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/discourse-analysis] Formally equivalent relations among the sentences of a coherent discourse are made explicit by using sentence transformations to put the text in a canonical form.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/discourse-analysis] Words and sentences with equivalent information then appear in the same column of an array.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/discourse-analysis] This work progressed over the next four decades (see references) into a science of sublanguage analysis (Kittredge & Lehrberger 1982), culminating in a demonstration of the informational structures in texts of a sublanguage of science, that of immunology (Harris et al.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/discourse-analysis] 1989), and a fully articulated theory of linguistic informational content (Harris 1991).
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/discourse-analysis] During this time, however, most linguists ignored such developments in favor of a succession of elaborate theories of sentence-level syntax and semantics.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/discourse-analysis] In January 1953, a linguist working for the American Bible Society, James A.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/discourse-analysis] Lauriault (*alt.* Loriot), needed to find answers to some fundamental errors in translating Quechua, in the Cuzco area of Peru.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/discourse-analysis] Following Harris's 1952 publications, he worked over the meaning and placement of each word in a collection of Quechua legends with a native speaker of Quechua and was able to formulate discourse rules that transcended the simple sentence structure.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/discourse-analysis] He then applied the process to Shipibo, another language of Eastern Peru.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/discourse-analysis] He taught the theory at the Summer Institute of Linguistics in Norman, Oklahoma, in the summers of 1956 and 1957 and entered the University of Pennsylvania to study with Harris in the interim year.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/discourse-analysis] He tried to publish a paper,*Shipibo Paragraph Structure*, but it was delayed until 1970 (Loriot & Hollenbach 1970).
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/discourse-analysis] In the meantime, Kenneth Lee Pike, a professor at the University of Michigan, taught the theory, and one of his students, Robert E.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/discourse-analysis] Harris's methodology disclosing the correlation of form with meaning was developed into a system for the computer-aided analysis of natural language by a team led by Naomi Sager at NYU, which has been applied to a number of sublanguage domains, most notably to medical informatics.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/discourse-analysis] In the late 1960s and 1970s, and without reference to this prior work, a variety of other approaches to a new cross-discipline of DA began to develop in most of the humanities and social sciences concurrently with, and related to, other disciplines.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/discourse-analysis] These include semiotics, psycholinguistics, sociolinguistics, and pragmatics.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/discourse-analysis] Many of these approaches, especially those influenced by the social sciences, favor a more dynamic study of oral talk-in-interaction.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/discourse-analysis] An example is "conversational analysis" (CA), which was influenced by the sociologist Harold Garfinkel, the founder of ethnomethodology.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/discourse-analysis] Although these approaches emphasize different aspects of language use, they all view language as social interaction and are concerned with the social contexts in which discourse is embedded.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/discourse-analysis] Often a distinction is made between 'local' structures of discourse (such as relations among sentences, propositions, and turns) and 'global' structures, such as overall topics and the schematic organization of discourses and conversations.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/discourse-analysis] For instance, many types of discourse begin with some kind of global 'summary', in titles, headlines, leads, abstracts, and so on.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/discourse-analysis] Political discourse analysis is a field of discourse analysis which focuses on discourse in political forums (such as debates, speeches, and hearings) as the phenomenon of interest.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/discourse-analysis] Policy analysis requires discourse analysis to be effective from the post-positivist perspective.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/discourse-analysis] Political discourse is the formal exchange of reasoned views as to which of several alternative courses of action should be taken to solve a societal problem.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] In philosophy, **empiricism** is an epistemological view which holds that true knowledge or justification comes either only or primarily from sensory experience and empirical evidence.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] It is one of several competing views within epistemology, along with rationalism and skepticism.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Empiricists argue that empiricism is a more reliable method of finding the truth than relying purely on logical reasoning, because humans have cognitive biases and limitations which lead to errors of judgement.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Empiricism emphasizes the central role of empirical evidence in the formation of ideas, rather than innate ideas or traditions.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Empiricists may argue that traditions (or customs) arise due to relations of previous sensory experiences.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Historically, empiricism was associated with the "blank slate" concept (*tabula rasa*), according to which the human mind is "blank" at birth and develops its thoughts only through later experience.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Empiricism in the philosophy of science emphasizes evidence, especially as discovered in experiments.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] It is a fundamental part of the scientific method that all hypotheses and theories must be tested against observations of the natural world rather than resting solely on *a priori* reasoning, intuition, or revelation.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Empiricism, often used by natural scientists, holds that "knowledge is based on experience" and that "knowledge is tentative and probabilistic, subject to continued revision and falsification".
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Empirical research, including experiments and validated measurement tools, guides the scientific method.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] The English term *empirical* derives from the Ancient Greek word ἐμπειρία, *empeiria*, which is cognate with and translates to the Latin *experientia*, from which the words *experience* and *experiment* are derived.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] A central concept in science and the scientific method is that conclusions must be *empirically* based on the evidence of the senses.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Both natural and social sciences use working hypotheses that are testable by observation and experiment.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] The term *semi-empirical* is sometimes used to describe theoretical methods that make use of basic axioms, established scientific laws, and previous experimental results to engage in reasoned model building and theoretical inquiry.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Philosophical empiricists hold no knowledge to be properly inferred or deduced unless it is derived from one's sense-based experience.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] However, many Enlightenment rationalists and empiricists still made concessions to each other.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] For example, the empiricist John Locke admitted that some knowledge (e.g. knowledge of God's existence) could be arrived at through intuition and reasoning alone.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Similarly, Robert Boyle, a prominent advocate of the experimental method, held that we also have innate ideas.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] At the same time, the main continental rationalists (Descartes, Spinoza, and Leibniz) were also advocates of the empirical "scientific method".
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Between 600 and 200 BCE, the Vaisheshika school of Hindu philosophy, founded by the ancient Indian philosopher Kanada, accepted perception and inference as the only two reliable sources of knowledge.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] This is enumerated in his work *Vaiśeṣika Sūtra*.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] The Charvaka school held similar beliefs, asserting that perception is the only reliable source of knowledge while inference obtains knowledge with uncertainty.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] The earliest Western proto-empiricists were the empiric school of ancient Greek medical practitioners, founded in 330 BCE.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Its members rejected the doctrines of the dogmatic school, preferring to rely on the observation of *phantasiai* (i.e., phenomena, the appearances).
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] The Empiric school was closely allied with the Pyrrhonist school of philosophy, which made the philosophical case for their proto-empiricism.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] The notion of *tabula rasa* ("clean slate" or "blank tablet") connotes a view of the mind as an originally blank or empty recorder (Locke used the words "white paper") on which experience leaves marks.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] This denies that humans have innate ideas.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Aristotle's explanation of how this was possible was not strictly empiricist in a modern sense, but rather based on his theory of potentiality and actuality, and experience of sense perceptions still requires the help of the active *nous*.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] These notions contrasted with Platonic notions of the human mind as an entity that pre-existed somewhere in the heavens, before being sent down to join a body on Earth (see Plato's *Phaedo* and *Apology*, as well as others).
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Aristotle was considered to give a more important position to sense perception than Plato, and commentators in the Middle Ages summarized one of his positions as "*nihil in intellectu nisi prius fuerit in sensu*" (Latin for "nothing in the intellect without first being in the senses").
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] This idea was later developed in ancient philosophy by the Stoic school, from about 330 BCE.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Stoic epistemology generally emphasizes that the mind starts blank, but acquires knowledge as the outside world is impressed upon it.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] During the Middle Ages (from the 5th to the 15th century CE) Aristotle's theory of *tabula rasa* was developed by Islamic philosophers starting with Al Farabi (c.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] 951 CE), developing into an elaborate theory by Avicenna (c.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] 980 – 1037 CE) and demonstrated as a thought experiment by Ibn Tufail.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] The intellect itself develops from a material intellect (*al-'aql al-hayulani*), which is a potentiality "that can acquire knowledge to the active intellect (*al-'aql al-fa'il*), the state of the human intellect in conjunction with the perfect source of knowledge".
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] So the immaterial "active intellect", separate from any individual person, is still essential for understanding to occur.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] The Latin translation of his philosophical novel, entitled *Philosophus Autodidactus*, published by Edward Pococke the Younger in 1671, had an influence on John Locke's formulation of *tabula rasa* in *An Essay Concerning Human Understanding*.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] A similar Islamic theological novel, *Theologus Autodidactus*, was written by the Arab theologian and physician Ibn al-Nafis in the 13th century.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] It also dealt with the theme of empiricism through the story of a feral child on a desert island, but departed from its predecessor by depicting the development of the protagonist's mind through contact with society rather than in isolation from society.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] During the 13th century Thomas Aquinas adopted into scholasticism the Aristotelian position that the senses are essential to the mind.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Bonaventure (1221–1274), one of Aquinas' strongest intellectual opponents, offered some of the strongest arguments in favour of the Platonic idea of the mind.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] In the late renaissance various writers began to question the medieval and classical understanding of knowledge acquisition in a more fundamental way.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] In political and historical writing Niccolò Machiavelli and his friend Francesco Guicciardini initiated a new realistic style of writing.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Machiavelli in particular was scornful of writers on politics who judged everything in comparison to mental ideals and demanded that people should study the "effectual truth" instead.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Telesio's influence can also be seen on the French philosophers René Descartes and Pierre Gassendi.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] The decidedly anti-Aristotelian and anti-clerical music theorist Vincenzo Galilei (c.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] The Italian word he used for "experiment" was *esperimento*.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] It is known that he was the essential pedagogical influence upon the young Galileo, his eldest son (cf.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] *Music and Science in the Age of Galileo Galilei*), arguably one of the most influential empiricists in history.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] In response to the early-to-mid-17th-century "continental rationalism", John Locke (1632–1704) proposed in *An Essay Concerning Human Understanding* (1689) a very influential view wherein the *only* knowledge humans can have is *a posteriori*, i.e., based upon experience.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Locke is famously attributed with holding the proposition that the human mind is a *tabula rasa*, a "blank tablet", in Locke's words "white paper", on which the experiences derived from sense impressions as a person's life proceeds are written.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] There are two sources of our ideas: sensation and reflection.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] In both cases, a distinction is made between simple and complex ideas.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] The former are unanalysable, and are broken down into primary and secondary qualities.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Primary qualities are essential for the object in question to be what it is.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Without specific primary qualities, an object would not be what it is.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] For example, an apple is an apple because of the arrangement of its atomic structure.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] If an apple were structured differently, it would cease to be an apple.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Secondary qualities are the sensory information we can perceive from its primary qualities.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] For example, an apple can be perceived in various colours, sizes, and textures but it is still identified as an apple.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Therefore, its primary qualities dictate what the object essentially is, while its secondary qualities define its attributes.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Complex ideas combine simple ones, and divide into substances, modes, and relations.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] According to Locke, our knowledge of things is a perception of ideas that are in accordance or discordance with each other, which is very different from the quest for certainty of Descartes.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] A generation later, the Irish Anglican bishop George Berkeley (1685–1753) determined that Locke's view immediately opened a door that would lead to eventual atheism.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] In response to Locke, he put forth in his *Treatise Concerning the Principles of Human Knowledge* (1710) an important challenge to empiricism in which things *only* exist either as a *result* of their being perceived, or by virtue of the fact that they are an entity doing the perceiving.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] (For Berkeley, God fills in for humans by doing the perceiving whenever humans are not around to do it.) In his text *Alciphron*, Berkeley maintained that any order humans may see in nature is the language or handwriting of God.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Berkeley's approach to empiricism would later come to be called subjective idealism.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Scottish philosopher David Hume (1711–1776) responded to Berkeley's criticisms of Locke, as well as other differences between early modern philosophers, and moved empiricism to a new level of skepticism.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Hume argued in keeping with the empiricist view that all knowledge derives from sense experience, but he accepted that this has implications not normally acceptable to philosophers.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] He wrote for example, "Locke divides all arguments into demonstrative and probable.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] On this view, we must say that it is only probable that all men must die or that the sun will rise to-morrow, because neither of these can be demonstrated.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Hume divided all of human knowledge into two categories: *relations of ideas* and *matters of fact* (see also Kant's analytic-synthetic distinction).
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Mathematical and logical propositions (e.g.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] "that the square of the hypotenuse is equal to the sum of the squares of the two sides") are examples of the first, while propositions involving some contingent observation of the world (e.g.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] "the sun rises in the East") are examples of the second.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] All of people's "ideas", in turn, are derived from their "impressions".
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] For Hume, an "impression" corresponds roughly with what we call a sensation.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] To remember or to imagine such impressions is to have an "idea".
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Ideas are therefore the faint copies of sensations.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Hume maintained that no knowledge, even the most basic beliefs about the natural world, can be conclusively established by reason.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Rather, he maintained, our beliefs are more a result of accumulated *habits*, developed in response to accumulated sense experiences.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Among his many arguments Hume also added another important slant to the debate about scientific method—that of the problem of induction.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Hume argued that it requires inductive reasoning to arrive at the premises for the principle of inductive reasoning, and therefore the justification for inductive reasoning is a circular argument.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Among Hume's conclusions regarding the problem of induction is that there is no certainty that the future will resemble the past.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Thus, as a simple instance posed by Hume, we cannot know with certainty by inductive reasoning that the sun will continue to rise in the East, but instead come to expect it to do so because it has repeatedly done so in the past.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Hume concluded that such things as belief in an external world and belief in the existence of the self were not rationally justifiable.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] According to Hume these beliefs were to be accepted nonetheless because of their profound basis in instinct and custom.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Hume's lasting legacy, however, was the doubt that his skeptical arguments cast on the legitimacy of inductive reasoning, allowing many skeptics who followed to cast similar doubt.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] According to an extreme empiricist theory known as phenomenalism, anticipated by the arguments of both Hume and George Berkeley, a physical object is a kind of construction out of our experiences.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Phenomenalism is the view that physical objects, properties, events (whatever is physical) are reducible to mental objects, properties, events.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Ultimately, only mental objects, properties, events, exist—hence the closely related term subjective idealism.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] By the phenomenalistic line of thinking, to have a visual experience of a real physical thing is to have an experience of a certain kind of group of experiences.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] This type of set of experiences possesses a constancy and coherence that is lacking in the set of experiences of which hallucinations, for example, are a part.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] As John Stuart Mill put it in the mid-19th century, matter is the "permanent possibility of sensation".
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Mill's empiricism went a significant step beyond Hume in still another respect: in maintaining that induction is necessary for *all* meaningful knowledge including mathematics.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Mill's empiricism thus held that knowledge of any kind is not from direct experience but an inductive inference from direct experience.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] The problems other philosophers have had with Mill's position center around the following issues: Firstly, Mill's formulation encounters difficulty when it describes what direct experience is by differentiating only between actual and possible sensations.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] This misses some key discussion concerning conditions under which such "groups of permanent possibilities of sensation" might exist in the first place.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Berkeley put God in that gap; the phenomenalists, including Mill, essentially left the question unanswered.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] In the end, lacking an acknowledgement of an aspect of "reality" that goes beyond mere "possibilities of sensation", such a position leads to a version of subjective idealism.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Questions of how floor beams continue to support a floor while unobserved, how trees continue to grow while unobserved and untouched by human hands, etc., remain unanswered, and perhaps unanswerable in these terms.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Secondly, Mill's formulation leaves open the unsettling possibility that the "gap-filling entities are purely possibilities and not actualities at all".
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Thirdly, Mill's position, by calling mathematics merely another species of inductive inference, misapprehends mathematics.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] It fails to fully consider the structure and method of mathematical science, the products of which are arrived at through an internally consistent deductive set of procedures which do not, either today or at the time Mill wrote, fall under the agreed meaning of induction.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] The phenomenalist phase of post-Humean empiricism ended by the 1940s, for by that time it had become obvious that statements about physical things could not be translated into statements about actual and possible sense data.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] If a physical object statement is to be translatable into a sense-data statement, the former must be at least deducible from the latter.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] But it came to be realized that there is no finite set of statements about actual and possible sense-data from which we can deduce even a single physical-object statement.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] The translating or paraphrasing statement must be couched in terms of normal observers in normal conditions of observation.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] There is, however, no *finite* set of statements that are couched in purely sensory terms and can express the satisfaction of the condition of the presence of a normal observer.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] According to phenomenalism, to say that a normal observer is present is to make the hypothetical statement that were a doctor to inspect the observer, the observer would appear to the doctor to be normal.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] But, of course, the doctor himself must be a normal observer.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] If we are to specify this doctor's normality in sensory terms, we must make reference to a second doctor who, when inspecting the sense organs of the first doctor, would himself have to have the sense data a normal observer has when inspecting the sense organs of a subject who is a normal observer.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] And if we are to specify in sensory terms that the second doctor is a normal observer, we must refer to a third doctor, and so on (also see the third man).
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Some of the key figures in this movement were Otto Neurath, Moritz Schlick and the rest of the Vienna Circle, along with A.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Ayer, Rudolf Carnap and Hans Reichenbach.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] The neopositivists subscribed to a notion of philosophy as the conceptual clarification of the methods, insights and discoveries of the sciences.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] They saw in the logical symbolism elaborated by Frege (1848–1925) and Bertrand Russell (1872–1970) a powerful instrument that could rationally reconstruct all scientific discourse into an ideal, logically perfect, language that would be free of the ambiguities and deformations of natural language.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] This gave rise to what they saw as metaphysical pseudoproblems and other conceptual confusions.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] By combining Frege's thesis that all mathematical truths are logical with the early Wittgenstein's idea that all logical truths are mere linguistic tautologies, they arrived at a twofold classification of all propositions: the "analytic" (*a priori*) and the "synthetic" (*a posteriori*).
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] On this basis, they formulated a strong principle of demarcation between sentences that have sense and those that do not: the so-called "verification principle".
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Any sentence that is not purely logical, or is unverifiable, is devoid of meaning.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] As a result, most metaphysical, ethical, aesthetic and other traditional philosophical problems came to be considered pseudoproblems.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] In the extreme empiricism of the neopositivists—at least before the 1930s—any genuinely synthetic assertion must be reducible to an ultimate assertion (or set of ultimate assertions) that expresses direct observations or perceptions.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] In later years, Carnap and Neurath abandoned this sort of *phenomenalism* in favor of a rational reconstruction of knowledge into the language of an objective spatio-temporal physics.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] That is, instead of translating sentences about physical objects into sense-data, such sentences were to be translated into so-called *protocol sentences*, for example, "*X* at location *Y* and at time *T* observes such and such".
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] The central theses of logical positivism (verificationism, the analytic–synthetic distinction, reductionism, etc.) came under sharp attack after World War II by thinkers such as Nelson Goodman, W.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Quine, Hilary Putnam, Karl Popper, and Richard Rorty.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] By the late 1960s, it had become evident to most philosophers that the movement had pretty much run its course, though its influence is still significant among contemporary analytic philosophers such as Michael Dummett and other anti-realists.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] In the late 19th and early 20th century, several forms of pragmatic philosophy arose.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] The ideas of pragmatism, in its various forms, developed mainly from discussions between Charles Sanders Peirce and William James when both men were at Harvard in the 1870s.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] James popularized the term "pragmatism", giving Peirce full credit for its patrimony, but Peirce later demurred from the tangents that the movement was taking, and redubbed what he regarded as the original idea with the name of "pragmaticism".
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Along with its *pragmatic theory of truth*, this perspective integrates the basic insights of empirical (experience-based) and rational (concept-based) thinking.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Charles Peirce (1839–1914) was highly influential in laying the groundwork for today's empirical scientific method.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Although Peirce severely criticized many elements of Descartes' peculiar brand of rationalism, he did not reject rationalism outright.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Indeed, he concurred with the main ideas of rationalism, most importantly the idea that rational concepts can be meaningful and the idea that rational concepts necessarily go beyond the data given by empirical observation.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] In later years he even emphasized the concept-driven side of the then ongoing debate between strict empiricism and strict rationalism, in part to counterbalance the excesses to which some of his cohorts had taken pragmatism under the "data-driven" strict-empiricist view.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Among Peirce's major contributions was to place inductive reasoning and deductive reasoning in a complementary rather than competitive mode, the latter of which had been the primary trend among the educated since David Hume wrote a century before.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] To this, Peirce added the concept of abductive reasoning.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] The combined three forms of reasoning serve as a primary conceptual foundation for the empirically based scientific method today.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Peirce's approach "presupposes that (1) the objects of knowledge are real things, (2) the characters (properties) of real things do not depend on our perceptions of them, and (3) everyone who has sufficient experience of real things will agree on the truth about them.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] According to Peirce's doctrine of fallibilism, the conclusions of science are always tentative.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] The rationality of the scientific method does not depend on the certainty of its conclusions, but on its self-corrective character: by continued application of the method science can detect and correct its own mistakes, and thus eventually lead to the discovery of truth".
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] In his Harvard "Lectures on Pragmatism" (1903), Peirce enumerated what he called the "three cotary propositions of pragmatism" (L: *cos, cotis* whetstone), saying that they "put the edge on the maxim of pragmatism".
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] First among these, he listed the peripatetic-thomist observation mentioned above, but he further observed that this link between sensory perception and intellectual conception is a two-way street.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] That is, it can be taken to say that whatever we find in the intellect is also incipiently in the senses.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Hence, if theories are theory-laden then so are the senses, and perception itself can be seen as a species of abductive inference, its difference being that it is beyond control and hence beyond critique—in a word, incorrigible.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] This in no way conflicts with the fallibility and revisability of scientific concepts, since it is only the immediate percept in its unique individuality or "thisness"—what the Scholastics called its *haecceity*—that stands beyond control and correction.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Scientific concepts, on the other hand, are general in nature, and transient sensations do in another sense find correction within them.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] This notion of perception as abduction has received periodic revivals in artificial intelligence and cognitive science research, most recently for instance with the work of Irvin Rock on *indirect perception*.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] James maintained that the empirically observed "directly apprehended universe needs ... no extraneous trans-empirical connective support", by which he meant to rule out the perception that there can be any value added by seeking supernatural explanations for natural phenomena.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] James' "radical empiricism" is thus *not* radical in the context of the term "empiricism", but is instead fairly consistent with the modern use of the term "empirical".
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] His method of argument in arriving at this view, however, still readily encounters debate within philosophy even today.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] John Dewey (1859–1952) modified James' pragmatism to form a theory known as instrumentalism.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] The role of sense experience in Dewey's theory is crucial, in that he saw experience as a unified totality of things through which everything else is interrelated.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Dewey's basic thought, in accordance with empiricism, was that reality is determined by past experience.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Therefore, humans adapt their past experiences of things to perform experiments upon and test the pragmatic values of such experience.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] The value of such experience is measured experientially and scientifically, and the results of such tests generate ideas that serve as instruments for future experimentation, in physical sciences as in ethics.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Thus, ideas in Dewey's system retain their empiricist flavour in that they are only known *a posteriori*.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/empiricism] Nativists (or rationalists), by contrast, argue that innate mental representations and specialized psychological mechanisms play a foundational role in explaining how the human mind acquires its knowledge and diverse cognitive capacities.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Happiness is closely linked to well-being and overall life satisfaction.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Studies have shown that individuals who experience higher levels of happiness tend to have better physical and mental health, stronger social relationships, and greater resilience in the face of adversity.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] The pursuit of happiness has been a central theme in philosophy and psychology for centuries.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] While there is no single, universally accepted definition of happiness, it is generally understood to be a state of mind characterized by positive emotions, a sense of purpose, and a feeling of fulfillment.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] "Happiness" is subject to debate on usage and meaning, and on possible differences in understanding by culture.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Some usages can include both of these factors.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Subjective well-being (swb) includes measures of current experience (emotions, moods, and feelings) and of life satisfaction.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] For instance Sonja Lyubomirsky has described happiness as "*the experience of joy, contentment, or positive well-being, combined with a sense that one's life is good, meaningful, and worthwhile.*" Eudaimonia, is a Greek term variously translated as happiness, welfare, flourishing, and blessedness.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Xavier Landes has proposed that happiness include measures of subjective well-being, mood and eudaimonia.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] These differing uses can give different results.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Whereas Nordic countries often score highest on swb surveys, South American countries score higher on affect-based surveys of current positive life experiencing.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] The implied meaning of the word may vary depending on context, qualifying happiness as a polyseme and a fuzzy concept.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] A further issue is when measurement is made; appraisal of a level of happiness at the time of the experience may be different from appraisal via memory at a later date.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Some users accept these issues, but continue to use the word because of its convening power.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] People have been trying to measure happiness for centuries.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] In 1780, the English utilitarian philosopher Jeremy Bentham proposed that as happiness was the primary goal of humans, it should be measured as a way of determining how well the government was performing.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Today, happiness is typically measured using self-report surveys.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Self-reporting is prone to cognitive biases and other sources of errors, such as peak–end rule.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Studies show that memories of felt emotions can be inaccurate.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Affective forecasting research shows that people are poor predictors of their future emotions, including how happy they will be.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Happiness economists are not overly concerned with philosophical and methodological issues and continue to use questionaries to measure average happiness of populations.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Since 2012, a World Happiness Report has been published.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Happiness is evaluated, as in "How happy are you with your life as a whole?", and in emotional reports, as in "How happy are you now?," and people seem able to use happiness as appropriate in these verbal contexts.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Using these measures, the report identifies the countries with the highest levels of happiness.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] In subjective well-being measures, the primary distinction is between cognitive life evaluations and emotional reports.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] The UK began to measure national well-being in 2012, following Bhutan, which had already been measuring gross national happiness.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Academic economists and international economic organizations are arguing for and developing multi-dimensional dashboards which combine subjective and objective indicators to provide a more direct and explicit assessment of human wellbeing.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] There are many different contributors to adult wellbeing, such as the point that happiness judgements partly reflect the presence of salient constraints, and that fairness, autonomy, community and engagement are key aspects of happiness and wellbeing throughout the life course.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Although these factors play a role in happiness, they do not all need to improve simultaneously to help one achieve an increase in happiness.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Happiness has been found to be quite stable over time.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] The happiness tends to increase with age, with young adults the least happy.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] As of 2016, no evidence of happiness causing improved physical health has been found; the topic is being researched at the Lee Kum Sheung Center for Health and Happiness at the Harvard T.H.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] A positive relationship has been suggested between the volume of the brain's gray matter in the right precuneus area and one's subjective happiness score.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Sonja Lyubomirsky has estimated that 50 percent of a given human's happiness level could be genetically determined, 10 percent is affected by life circumstances and situation, and a remaining 40 percent of happiness is subject to self-control.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] When discussing genetics and their effects on individuals it is important to first understand that genetics do not predict behavior.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] It is possible for genes to increase the likelihood of individuals being happier compared to others, but they do not 100 percent predict behavior.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] At this point in scientific research, it has been hard to find a lot of evidence to support this idea that happiness is affected in some way by genetics.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] In a 2016 study, Michael Minkov and Michael Harris Bond found that a gene by the name of SLC6A4 was not a good predictor of happiness level in humans.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] On the other hand, there have been many studies that have found genetics to be a key part in predicting and understanding happiness in humans.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] In a review article discussing many studies on genetics and happiness, they discussed the common findings.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] The author found an important factor that has affected scientist findings this being how happiness is measured.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] For example, in certain studies when subjective wellbeing is measured as a trait heredity is found to be higher, about 70 to 90 percent.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] In another study, 11,500 unrelated genotypes were studied, and the conclusion was the heritability was only 12 to 18 percent.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Overall, this article found the common percent of heredity was about 20 to 50 percent.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Theories on how to achieve happiness include "encountering unexpected positive events", "seeing a significant other", and "basking in the acceptance and praise of others".
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Some others believe that happiness is not solely derived from external, momentary pleasures.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Waldinger found that those who were happiest and healthier reported strong interpersonal relationships.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Research showed that adequate sleep contributes to well-being.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Good mental health and good relationships contribute more to happiness than income does.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Santos course titled "*Psychology and the Good Life"* became the most popular course in the history of Yale University and was made available for free online to non-Yale students.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] In 2020, the course had 1,153,744 people enroll 10.5 million people visit the site.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Santos explains that during the COVID-19 crisis people were looking for evidence-based ways to improve not only their physical health, but also their mental health.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Some commentators focus on the difference between the hedonistic tradition of seeking pleasant and avoiding unpleasant experiences, and the eudaimonic tradition of living life in a full and deeply satisfying way.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Viktor Frankl, a psychiatrist and prisoner in the Nazi concentration camps during World War II, noticed that those who lost hope soon died, while those who held to meaning and purpose tended to live on.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Frankl observed that joy and misery had more to do with a person's perspective and choice than with their surroundings.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Love, as manifest in thoroughly encountering another person or experience.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Finding meaning in unavoidable suffering, such as seeing it as a sacrifice or learning opportunity.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Psychologist Robert Emmons has identified the centrality of goals in pursuing happiness.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] He found that when humans pursue meaningful projects and activities without primarily focusing on happiness, happiness often results as a by-product.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Indicators of meaningfulness predict positive effects on life, while lack of meaning predicts negative states such as psychological distress.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Emmons summarizes the four categories of meaning which have appeared throughout various studies.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] He proposes to call them WIST, or work, intimacy, spirituality, and transcendence.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Throughout life, one's views of happiness and what brings happiness can evolve.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] In early and emerging adulthood many people focus on seeking happiness through friends, objects, and money.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Middle aged-adults generally transition from searching for object-based happiness to looking for happiness in money and relationships.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] In older adulthood, people tend to focus more on personal peace and lasting relationships (ex. children, spouse, grandchildren).
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Antti Kauppinen, a Swedish philosopher and phenomenological researcher, posited that the perception of time affects the change in focus throughout life.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] In early adulthood, most view life optimistically, looking to the future and seeing an entire life ahead of them.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Those that fall into the middle life, see that life has passed behind them as well as seeing more life ahead.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Those in older adulthood often see their lives as behind them.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] This shift in perspective causes a shift in the pursuit of happiness from more tactile, object based happiness, to social and relational based happiness.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Maslow's hierarchy of needs is a pyramid depicting the levels of human needs, psychological, and physical.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] When a human being ascends the steps of the pyramid, self-actualization is reached.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Beyond the routine of needs fulfillment, Maslow envisioned moments of extraordinary experience, known as peak experiences, profound moments of love, understanding, happiness, or rapture, during which a person feels more whole, alive, self-sufficient, and yet a part of the world.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] This is similar to the flow concept of Mihály Csíkszentmihályi.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] The concept of flow is the idea that after our basic needs are met we can achieve greater happiness by altering our consciousness by becoming so engaged in a task that we lose our sense of time.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Our intense focus causes us to forget any other issues, which in return promotes positive emotions.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Erich Fromm said "Happiness is the indication that man has found the answer to the problem of human existence: the productive realization of his potentialities and thus, simultaneously, being one with the world and preserving the integrity of his self.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Self-determination theory relates intrinsic motivation to three needs: competence, autonomy, and relatedness.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Competence refers to an individual's ability to be effective in their interactions with the environment, autonomy refers to a person's flexibility in choice and decision making, and relatedness is the need to establish warm, close personal relationships.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Ronald Inglehart has traced cross-national differences in the level of happiness based on data from the World Values Survey.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] He finds that the extent to which a society allows free choice has a major impact on happiness.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] When basic needs are satisfied, the degree of happiness depends on economic and cultural factors that enable free choice in how people live their lives.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Happiness also depends on religion in countries where free choice is constrained.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] The idea of motivational hedonism is the theory that pleasure is the aim for human life.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Since 2000 the field of positive psychology, which focuses on the study of happiness and human flourishing rather than maladjusted behavior or illness, expanded drastically in terms of scientific publications.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Courage, which includes bravery, persistence, integrity, and vitality.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Humanity, which includes love, kindness, and social intelligence.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Justice, which includes leadership, fairness, and loyalty.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Temperance, which includes self-regulation, prudence, forgiveness, humility, patience and modesty.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Transcendence, which includes religious/spirituality, hope, gratitude, appreciation of beauty and excellence, and humor.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Seligman later formalized positive psychology with the PERMA model (Positive Emotion, Engagement, Relationships, Meaning, and Accomplishment), introduced in 2011.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] The model has since been widely used in positive psychology research as a framework for understanding well-being.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Numerous short-term self-help interventions have been developed and demonstrated to improve happiness.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Yale researcher Emma Seppälä has emphasized the importance of compassion for others, balanced with self-compassion.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Compassion for others may involve service and volunteering, or simply reaching out to connect, show gratitude, or draw others together.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] A person's level of subjective well-being is determined by many different factors and social influences prove to be a strong one.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Results from the famous Framingham Heart Study indicate that friends three degrees of separation away (that is, friends of friends of friends) can affect a person's happiness.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Various writers, including Camus and Tolle, have written that the act of searching or seeking for happiness is incompatible with being happy.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] John Stuart Mill believed that for the great majority of people happiness is best achieved en passant, rather than striving for it directly.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] This meant no self-consciousness, scrutiny, self-interrogation, dwelling on, thinking about, imagining or questioning on one's happiness.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Cognitive behavioral therapy is a popular therapeutic method used to change habits by changing thoughts and problematic behaviors.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] It focuses on emotional regulation and uses a lot of positive psychology practices.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] It is often used for people with depression, anxiety, or addictions and works towards how to lead a happier life.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Common processes in cognitive behavioral therapy are reframing thoughts from problematic thinking patterns by replacing them with beneficial or supportive ones, roleplaying, finding beneficial coping skills, and choosing new activities that support desired behaviors and avoid negative behaviors.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Coined by Harvard professor of psychology and author of "Stumbling on Happiness", Daniel Gilbert, synthetic happiness is the happiness we make for ourselves.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] In his TedTalk titled, the surprising science of happiness, Gilbert explains that everyone possesses a "psychological immune system" that helps to regulate our emotional reactions.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Through research that he studied and held, he and his team found that personal happiness is largely based on personal perception.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Synthetic happiness as an idea has become more popular as people attempt to define happiness as a journey instead of a destination.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Happiness research understands "happiness" as "life satisfaction" or "well-being".
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Since it has proved difficult to find a definition of happiness, individual people are instead asked how happy they feel.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Numerous surveys are then summarized and analyzed using static methods.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] For example, individuals who report high happiness on scales smile more often, exhibit more social behavior, are more helpful, and are less likely to commit suicide.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] For this reason, happiness indices determined on the basis of the survey are considered reliable by happiness researchers.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] A meta analysis of 2023 evaluated evidence for common happiness-boosting strategies.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] The study aimed to shed light on the effectiveness of these strategies and their impact on subjective well-being.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] As a first step, the authors analyzed numerous media articles on happiness to identify the five most commonly recommended strategies, these were: expressing gratitude, enhancing sociability, exercising, practicing mindfulness/meditation, and increasing exposure to nature.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Next, the published scientific literature was searched but limited to the above-described high-quality criteria that tested the effects of these strategies on subjective well-being in everyday individuals.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Only 10% of the initially retrieved studies met those rigorous criteria.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] The findings revealed that unlike so far suggested by scientific studies, there is currently still a lack of robust scientific evidence to support some of the most frequently suggested happiness strategies.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Among the five most common happiness strategies, there was "reasonably solid evidence" of positive effects from a) Gratitude messages or lists, b) conversations with strangers or Gratitude and sociability – that is, establishing and maintaining social relationships.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] In contrast, no convincing evidence could be found that c) sports, d) mindfulness training, or e) walks in the countryside make people happier.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] There is a wealth of cross-sectional studies on happiness and physical health that shows consistent positive relationships.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Follow-up studies appear to show that happiness does not predict longevity in sick populations, but that it does predict longevity among healthy populations.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Other positive effects of happiness and being in a good mood, that have been studied and confirmed, are that happier people tend to be more helpful, attentive, and generous to others, as well as to themselves.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Happy people also have been shown to act more cooperatively and less aggressively, and be more likely to help others in need.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] They were also found to be more sociable and communicative.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] More positive effects that happiness seems to evoke are creative problem solving, persisting through challenges, more intrinsic motivation for work related or responsible tasks, and being more effective at using efficient decision-making strategies.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] While some believe that success breeds happiness, Lyubomirsky, King and Diener found that happiness precedes success in income, relationships, marriages, work performance, and health.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Low mood is correlated with many negative life outcomes such as suicide, poor health, substance abuse, and low life expectancy.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] By extension, happiness protects from those negative outcomes.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] June Gruber argued that happiness may trigger a person to be more sensitive, more gullible, less successful, and more likely to undertake high risk behaviours.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] She also conducted studies suggesting that seeking happiness can have negative effects, such as failure to meet over-high expectations.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Iris Mauss has shown that the more people strive for happiness, the more likely they will set up too high of standards and feel disappointed.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] One study shows that women who value happiness more tend to react less positively to happy emotions.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] A 2012 study found that psychological well-being was higher for people who experienced both positive and negative emotions.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Jeremy Bentham believed that public policy should attempt to maximize happiness, and he even attempted to estimate a "hedonic calculus".
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Thomas Jefferson put the "pursuit of happiness" on the same level as life and liberty in the United States Declaration of Independence.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Presently, many countries and organizations regularly measure population happiness through large-scale surveys, e.g., Bhutan.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Richer nations tend to have higher measures of happiness than poorer nations.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] The relationship between wealth and happiness is not linear and the same GDP increase in poor countries will have more effect on happiness than in wealthy countries.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Some political scientists argue that life satisfaction is positively related to the social democratic model of a generous social safety net, pro-worker labor market regulations, and strong labor unions.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Others argue that happiness is strongly correlated with economic freedom, preferably within the context of a western mixed economy, with free press and a democracy.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Personal happiness can be affected by cultural factors.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Hedonism appears to be more strongly related to happiness in more individualistic cultures.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Forcing people to marry and stay married can have adverse consequences.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Research has shown that unhappily married couples suffer 3–25 times the risk of developing clinical depression.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] One theory is that higher SWB in richer countries is related to their more individualistic cultures.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Individualistic cultures may satisfy intrinsic motivations to a higher degree than collectivistic cultures, and fulfilling intrinsic motivations, as opposed to extrinsic motivations, may relate to greater levels of happiness, leading to more happiness in individualistic cultures.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Cultural views on happiness have changed over time.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] For instance Western concern about childhood being a time of happiness has occurred only since the 19th century.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Not all cultures seek to maximize happiness, and some cultures are averse to happiness.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] It has been found in Western cultures that individual happiness is the most important.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Some other cultures have opposite views and tend to be aversive to the idea of individual happiness.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] For example, people living in Eastern Asian cultures focus more on the need for happiness within relationships with others and even find personal happiness to be harmful to fulfilling happy social relationships.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] People in countries with high cultural religiosity tend to relate their life satisfaction less to their emotional experiences than people in more secular countries.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Happiness forms a central theme of Buddhist teachings.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] For ultimate freedom from suffering, the Noble Eightfold Path leads its practitioner to Nirvana, a state of everlasting peace.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Ultimate happiness is only achieved by overcoming craving in all forms.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] More mundane forms of happiness, such as acquiring wealth and maintaining good friendships, are also recognized as worthy goals for lay people (see *sukha*).
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Buddhism also encourages the generation of loving kindness and compassion, the desire for the happiness and welfare of all beings.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] In Advaita Vedanta, the ultimate goal of life is happiness, in the sense that duality between Atman and Brahman is transcended and one realizes oneself to be the Self in all.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Patanjali, author of the Yoga Sutras, wrote exhaustively on the psychological and ontological roots of bliss.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Furthermore, the Bhagavad Gita teaches people to act without thinking of the result because attachment to results can lead to stress and aggression.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] However, the Gita still insists that people act to the best of their ability with full energy and skill.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] By focusing only on the work and the fruits of the action, people can give full concentration without letting anxiety hamper over.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] He argued that if one did not feel satisfaction or pleasure in nourishing one's "vital force" with "righteous deeds", then that force would shrivel up (Mencius, 6A:15 2A:2).
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] More specifically, he mentions the experience of intoxicating joy if one celebrates the practice of the great virtues, especially through music.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Happiness or *simcha* in Judaism is considered an important element in the service of God.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] A popular teaching by Rabbi Nachman of Breslov, a 19th-century Chassidic Rabbi, is "*Mitzvah Gedolah Le'hiyot Besimcha Tamid*," it is a great mitzvah (commandment) to always be in a state of happiness.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] When a person is happy they are much more capable of serving God and going about their daily activities than when depressed or upset.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] In Christianity, the ultimate end of human existence consists in felicity, Latin equivalent to the Greek *eudaimonia* ("blessed happiness"), described by the 13th-century philosopher-theologian Thomas Aquinas as a beatific vision of God's essence in the next life.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Human complexities, like reason and cognition, can produce well-being or happiness, but such form is limited and transitory.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] In temporal life, the contemplation of God, the infinitely Beautiful, is the supreme delight of the will.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] *Beatitudo*, or perfect happiness, as complete well-being, is to be attained not in this life, but the next.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Al-Ghazali, the Sufi thinker, wrote that "The Alchemy of Happiness" is a manual of religious instruction that is used throughout the Muslim world and widely practiced today.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Furthermore, in some Sufi traditions, rituals involving devotional songs (quavvāli) are performed to arouse mystical love and bring participants closer to God.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Joyce Flueckiger, in her book called *In Amma's Healing Room*, explains that a participant says that happiness is born from the poetry.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Philosophy of happiness is often discussed in conjunction with ethics.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Traditional European societies, inherited from the Greeks and from Christianity, often linked happiness with morality.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] In this context, morality was the performance in a specific role in a certain kind of social life.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Happiness remains a difficult term for moral philosophy.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Throughout the history of moral philosophy, there has been an oscillation between attempts to define morality in terms of consequences leading to happiness or defining it as nothing to do with happiness at all.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] In psychology, connections between happiness and morality have been studied in a variety of ways.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Empirical research suggests that laypeople's judgments of a person's happiness in part depend on perceptions of that person's morality, suggesting that judgments of others' happiness involve moral evaluation.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] A large body of research also suggests that engaging in prosocial behavior can increase happiness.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Ethicists have made arguments for how humans should behave, either individually or collectively, based on the resulting happiness of such behavior.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Utilitarians, such as John Stuart Mill and Jeremy Bentham, advocated the greatest happiness principle as a guide for ethical behavior.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] This principle states that actions are proportionately right or wrong by how much happiness or unhappiness they bring.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Mill defines happiness as that which brings about an intended pleasure and avoids an unnecessary pain, and he defines unhappiness as the reverse, namely an action that brings about pain and not pleasure.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] He is quick to specify that pleasure and pain are to be understood in an Epicurean light, referring chiefly to the higher human pleasures of increased intellect, feelings, and moral sentiments not what one might call beastly pleasures of mere animal appetites.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Critics of this view include Thomas Carlyle, Ferdinand Tönnies and others within the German philosophical tradition.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] They posit that a greater happiness is to be found in choosing to suffer for others, rather than allowing others to suffer for them, declaring this to be a form of satisfying, and heroic, nobility.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Many studies have observed the effects of volunteerism (as a form of altruism) on happiness and health and have consistently found that those who exhibit volunteerism also have better current and future health and well-being.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] In a study of older adults, those who volunteered had higher life satisfaction and will to live, and less depression, anxiety, and somatization.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Volunteerism and helping behavior have not only been shown to improve mental health but physical health and longevity as well, attributable to the activity and social integration it encourages.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] One study examined the physical health of mothers who volunteered over 30 years and found that 52% of those who did not belong to a volunteer organization experienced a major illness while only 36% of those who did volunteer experienced one.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] A study on adults aged 55 and older found that during the four-year study period, people who volunteered for two or more organizations had a 63% lower likelihood of dying.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] After controlling for prior health status, it was determined that volunteerism accounted for a 44% reduction in mortality.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Aristotle described *eudaimonia* (Greek: εὐδαιμονία) as the goal of human thought and action.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Eudaimonia is often translated to mean happiness, but some scholars contend that "human flourishing" may be a more accurate translation.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Aristotle's use of the term in Nicomachiean Ethics extends beyond the general sense of happiness.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] In the *Nicomachean Ethics*, written in 350 BCE, Aristotle stated that happiness (also being well and doing well) is the only thing that humans desire for their own sake, unlike riches, honour, health or friendship.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] He observed that men sought riches, or honour, or health not only for their own sake but also in order to be happy.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] For Aristotle the term *eudaimonia*, which is translated as 'happiness' or 'flourishing' is an activity rather than an emotion or a state.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Eudaimonia (Greek: εὐδαιμονία) is a classical Greek word consists of the word "eu" ("good" or "well-being") and "daimōn" ("spirit" or "minor deity", used by extension to mean one's lot or fortune).
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Thus understood, the happy life is the good life, that is, a life in which a person fulfills human nature in an excellent way.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Specifically, Aristotle argued that the good life is the life of excellent rational activity.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] He arrived at this claim with the "Function Argument".
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Basically, if it is right, every living thing has a function, that which it uniquely does.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] For Aristotle human function is to reason, since it is that alone which humans uniquely do.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] And performing one's function well, or excellently, is good.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] According to Aristotle, the life of excellent rational activity is the happy life.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] The key question Aristotle seeks to answer is "What is the ultimate purpose of human existence?" A lot of people are seeking pleasure, health, and a good reputation.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] It is true that those have a value, but none of them can occupy the place of the greatest good for which humanity aims.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] It may seem like all goods are a means to obtain happiness, but Aristotle said that happiness is always an end in itself.
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] Friedrich Nietzsche critiqued the English Utilitarians' focus on attaining the greatest happiness, stating that "Man does not strive for happiness, only the Englishman does".
[src:michael-argyle-psychologist/happiness] These small, "last men" who seek after only their own pleasure and health, avoiding all danger, exertion, difficulty, challenge, struggle are meant to seem contemptible to Nietzsche's reader.
